  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">NIHR RIGHT3: Intervention to screen and treat multimorbidity in high-risk patients.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. To confirm the prevalence of multimorbidity in patients attending acute hospital services in Malawi and Tanzania.
2. To create a strategy to recognise and treat multimorbidity using point-of-care tests incorporated into the emergency care pathways in Malawi and Tanzania, maximising acceptability to patients and healthcare workers, and optimising the impact of available resources.
3. To test the optimised emergency care pathway intervention with a primary outcome of hospital admission-free survival three months after hospital admission</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">A UK and low-and-middle-income-country (LMIC) research partnership that aims to design and test a system which identifies patients suffering from multiple diseases (multimorbidity) when they seek emergency care in hospitals in Malawi and Tanzania. This could improve early disease treatment (reducing death), and ensure better follow-up (preventing complications, disability, and hospital readmission). The research project is being implemented by Malawi Liverpool Wellcome Trust (Malawi), Kilimanjaro Christian Medical Centre (Tanzania) and Muhimbili University (Tanzania), in collaboration with Liverpool School of Tropical Medicine (UK), between 01-09-2021 and 31-12-2025.</narrative>
  </description>
